07569nam a22007815i 9780773589971DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735899717 a10.1515/97807735899712doi  a(DE-B1597)654586  a(OCoLC)862544793  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBD171b.T82 2013eb 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a1212231 aZuidervaart, Lambert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTruth Matters :bKnowledge, Politics, Ethics, Religion /cLambert Zuidervaart, Ronnie Shuker, Matthew J. Klaassen, Allyson Carr. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tTruth and Knowledge -- tHow Not to Be an Anti-realist: Habermas, Truth, and Justification -- tRadical Constructivism, Education, and Truth as Life-Giving Disclosure -- tThe Jelly and the Shot: Laying down the Law for Pragmatism in Quantum Physics -- tCognitive Diversity, Conceptual Schemes, and Truth -- tTruth and Politics -- tExposure and Disclosure: The Risk of Hermeneutical Truth in Democratic Politics -- tTruthfulness, Discourse, and the Problem of Pluralism -- tA Comparative Ethics Approach to the Concept of Bearing Witness: A Practice in Christian Theology and Journalism -- tNarrative Truth in Canadian Historical Fiction: In between Veracity and Imagination -- tTruth and Ethics -- tTruth, Truthfulness, and the I-Self Relationship -- tDoes Truth Matter to Ethics? Kierkegaard, Ethics, and the Subjectivity of Truth -- tTheories of Concepts and Moral Truth -- tEducating for Truthfulness -- tTruth and Religion -- tTruth Unveiled: Balthasar and the Contemplation of Christian Truth -- tTruth as “Being Trued”: Intersections between Ontological Truth in Aquinas and the Contemporary Anthropology of Religion -- tBedevilling Truth: “What Have I to Do with Thee?” -- tA Concept of Artistic Truth Prompted by Biblical Wisdom Literature -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy should we seek and tell the truth? Does anyone know what truth is? Many are skeptical about the relevance of truth. Truth Matters endeavours to show why truth is important in a world where the very idea of truth is contested. Putting philosophers in conversation with educators, literary scholars, physicists, political theorists, and theologians, Truth Matters ranges across both analytic and continental philosophy and draws on the ideas of thinkers such as Aquinas, Balthasar, Brandom, Davidson, Dooyeweerd, Gadamer, Habermas, Kierkegaard, Plantinga, Ricoeur, and Wolterstorff. Some essays attempt to provide a systematic account of truth, while others wrestle with the question of how truth is told and what it means to live truthfully. Contributors address debates between realists and anti-realists, explore issues surrounding relativism and constructivism in education and the social sciences, examine the politics of truth telling and the ethics of authenticity, and consider various religious perspectives on truth. Most scholars agree that truth is propositional, being expressed in statements that are subject to proof or disproof. This book goes a step farther: yes, propositional truth is important, but truth is more than propositional. To recognize how it is more than propositional is crucial for understanding why truth truly matters. Contributors include Doug Blomberg (ICS), Allyson Carr (ICS), Jeffrey Dudiak (King’s University College), Olaf Ellefson (York University), Gerrit Glas (VU University Amsterdam), Gill K. Goulding (Regis College), Jay Gupta (Mills College), Clarence Joldersma (Calvin College), Matthew J. Klaassen (ICS), John Jung Park (Duke University), Pamela J. Reeve (St. Augustine’s Seminary), Amy Richards (World Affairs Council of Western Michigan), Calvin Seerveld (ICS), Ronnie Shuker (ICS), Adam Smith (Brandeis University), John Van Rys (Redeemer University College), Darren Walhof (Grand Valley State University), Matthew Walhout (Calvin College), and Lambert Zuidervaart (ICS).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aTruthvCongresses. 0aTruthxCongresses. 0aTruth. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBlomberg, Doug, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarr, Allyson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCarr, Allyson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDudiak, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllefson, Olaf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlas, Gerrit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoulding, Gill K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Jay A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoldersma, Clarence W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaassen, Matthew J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKlaassen, Matthew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPark, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReeve, Pamela J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichards, Amy D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRys, John Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeerveld, Calvin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc